//////////////////
#include <stdio.h>
int main()
{
    int *ptr, a = 10;
    ptr = &a;
    *ptr += 1;
    printf("%d,%d\n", *ptr, a);
}
/////////////////////////////// 
++(*ptr)   ===  value is pre-incremented in pointer
//  ++ptr     ===  Pointer addreess will increment (depends data type)

/////////////////////
🔹 Step 1: Variable Declaration
int *ptr, a = 10;
a is a normal integer variable → value = 10
ptr is a pointer to an integer (it can store address of an int)

👉 Memory view (example):

a = 10   (stored at address say 1000)
ptr = ?  (not initialized yet)
🔹 Step 2: Assign Address
ptr = &a;
&a means address of variable a
Now ptr stores that address

👉 Memory view:

a   = 10     (address 1000)
ptr = 1000   (points to 'a')
🔹 Step 3: Dereference and Modify
*ptr += 1;

Break it down:

*ptr → go to address stored in ptr → access value of a
So *ptr is actually same as a

👉 Equivalent to:

a = a + 1;

👉 After execution:

a = 11

Memory:

a   = 11     (address 1000)
ptr = 1000   (still pointing to 'a')
🔹 Step 4: Print Values
printf("%d,%d\n", *ptr, a);
*ptr → value at address → 11
a → 11

👉 Output:

11,11
